1
00:00:00,340 --> 00:00:10,160
This is your first time, or second time. We're really glad that you've chosen to be here, and I'm Pastor Kirk, and it's a joy to share with you.

2
00:00:10,760 --> 00:00:13,980
And if you are one of our veteran members or regular attenders, it's good to have you back.

3
00:00:14,340 --> 00:00:20,120
We are now in the third installment of a series as we study and go through a book this fall.

4
00:00:20,120 --> 00:00:30,000
We're studying The Case for Faith, which is Lee Strobel's book that helps us talk intelligently about who God is and about why we believe the things we believe.

5
00:00:30,340 --> 00:00:36,300
As we are answering questions of our children, of our grandchildren, of our colleagues, friends at work, in the office, you name it.

6
00:00:37,120 --> 00:00:45,040
These tough questions that we're answering this fall are the ones you're most likely to encounter as we share the good news of Jesus Christ.

7
00:00:45,460 --> 00:00:52,400
And so this morning we talk about this big challenging issue of the creation versus the concept of evolution.

8
00:00:52,900 --> 00:00:55,360
Now I'm going to try and tackle all of that in about 25 minutes.

9
00:00:55,360 --> 00:00:59,700
So y'all pray for me this morning because that's a big challenge today.

10
00:01:01,740 --> 00:01:07,700
I also want to say this is probably the most lecture-style message I've given in quite a while.

11
00:01:07,800 --> 00:01:12,620
So put your thinking caps on, take some notes, get a copy of the tape if some of this goes beyond you,

12
00:01:12,680 --> 00:01:15,080
because there's a lot of scientific stuff, a lot of biblical stuff.

13
00:01:15,360 --> 00:01:20,820
I want to cram a lot in here, because I want you to be armed as we share the truth with people.

14
00:01:20,820 --> 00:01:25,920
I'd like to begin this morning by just sharing what Time Magazine wrote in December of the 99 issue.

15
00:01:25,920 --> 00:01:34,920
It says up here on the screen, Charles Darwin didn't want to murder God, as he once put it, but he did.

16
00:01:35,750 --> 00:01:37,250
That's Time Magazine's interpretation.

17
00:01:39,030 --> 00:01:45,750
Michael Denton, a molecular biologist, has a different approach to this, and he writes this.

18
00:01:47,130 --> 00:01:53,410
Evolutionary theory is still, as it was in Darwin's time, a highly speculative hypothesis,

19
00:01:53,410 --> 00:02:00,290
entirely without direct factual support, and very far from that self-evident axiom some of its more

20
00:02:00,290 --> 00:02:05,900
aggressive advocates would have us believe. Two different worldviews again. Two different

21
00:02:05,900 --> 00:02:12,060
intellectual positions at war over this issue that has such importance to who we are and to

22
00:02:12,060 --> 00:02:17,420
our faith and to whether there is a God and is he there for us to worship. I'm going to approach

23
00:02:17,420 --> 00:02:21,920
this topic this morning really from two angles. The scientific discussion is the first part,

24
00:02:21,920 --> 00:02:26,060
And then I'm going to move into the biblical discussion and the second part.

25
00:02:26,500 --> 00:02:29,780
Now, both of these issues are nowhere going to be treated exhaustively.

26
00:02:30,440 --> 00:02:34,480
There's no way I can pour through the volumes and volumes to wrestle adequately,

27
00:02:34,800 --> 00:02:41,120
but I'm hoping that I will pique your interest and give you places to start investigating on your own.

28
00:02:41,340 --> 00:02:46,240
But I think by the end of this message, you will have some tools in your belt, so to speak,

29
00:02:46,240 --> 00:02:51,360
that you can share with somebody else and be intelligent as you talk about these issues.

30
00:02:51,920 --> 00:02:53,160
And so that's where we're going.

31
00:02:53,280 --> 00:02:56,580
First of all this morning, then, the scientific discussion.

32
00:02:56,960 --> 00:03:03,520
The Bible says in its opening statements, Genesis 1-1, it says,

33
00:03:03,660 --> 00:03:08,200
In the beginning, God created the heavens and the earth.

34
00:03:10,300 --> 00:03:11,180
God created.

35
00:03:11,950 --> 00:03:15,970
For God to create, there's an assumption that there is a God to create.

36
00:03:17,500 --> 00:03:24,310
On the flip side, the counter position to that comes from Dr. William Provine of Cornell University.

37
00:03:24,730 --> 00:03:27,290
who in a number of his different writings and stuff,

38
00:03:27,350 --> 00:03:29,130
he boils down the five conclusions

39
00:03:29,130 --> 00:03:31,150
according to Darwin's theory,

40
00:03:31,890 --> 00:03:34,290
and his conclusions are as follows.

41
00:03:34,990 --> 00:03:37,810
Number one, there's no evidence for God.

42
00:03:39,420 --> 00:03:41,560
There's no life after death.

43
00:03:42,540 --> 00:03:46,060
There's no absolute foundation for right and wrong.

44
00:03:47,210 --> 00:03:49,170
There's no ultimate meaning for life.

45
00:03:50,260 --> 00:03:52,620
And people don't really have free will.

46
00:03:54,770 --> 00:03:56,230
Huge conclusions.

47
00:03:56,750 --> 00:04:00,630
Huge issues for us as a people to wrestle with.

48
00:04:01,560 --> 00:04:05,840
Now, in popular culture, if you just kind of ask the man or the woman on the street today,

49
00:04:06,360 --> 00:04:11,600
the evolutionary argument, for the most part, is considered basically a done deal.

50
00:04:12,120 --> 00:04:16,960
If you went over to Starbucks and just kind of asked some people at random what they thought about evolution,

51
00:04:16,960 --> 00:04:25,420
the dominant thinking in contemporary culture is, it's straight up, been settled, it's over, we've done that, we're on to new things.

52
00:04:27,550 --> 00:04:29,670
There's no more need for discussion.

53
00:04:30,710 --> 00:04:34,010
Richard Dawkins, the famous atheist and biologist, wrote this.

54
00:04:34,010 --> 00:04:38,870
He said, Darwin made it possible to be an intellectually fulfilled atheist.

55
00:04:42,720 --> 00:04:48,520
I'm going to show you a scene from a film that came out in the early part of last century

56
00:04:48,520 --> 00:04:54,290
from Fantasia, from Disney Studios, one of their first great works of animation.

57
00:04:54,770 --> 00:04:59,770
And from that film, they summarize the evolutionary argument very well.

58
00:04:59,770 --> 00:07:08,250
take a look at Fantasia. How many times have your children, how many times have you seen that

59
00:07:08,250 --> 00:07:16,080
whole argument laid out simply like that? Open and shut case. It's obvious. It's in film. It's

60
00:07:16,080 --> 00:07:24,420
in literature. It's on television. It's everywhere. Darwin wins the day. God is out. But I'm going to

61
00:07:24,420 --> 00:07:31,080
counter this morning with this. Is it really that simple? Is that depiction really how it happens?

62
00:07:31,080 --> 00:07:36,340
And are we to base our entire life on that set of values that comes underneath that?

63
00:07:36,380 --> 00:07:40,320
Because the values are, there's no need for God, there's no life after death,

64
00:07:40,360 --> 00:07:42,060
there's no foundation for right and wrong.

65
00:07:42,940 --> 00:07:45,980
Are we surprised today that we live amoral lives

66
00:07:45,980 --> 00:07:50,320
if ultimately you are simply a monkey's uncle or came out of the slime?

67
00:07:51,580 --> 00:07:53,380
There really is no foundation for right or wrong.

68
00:07:53,460 --> 00:07:56,320
There's no ultimate meaning for life, and people don't have any free will.

69
00:07:56,400 --> 00:07:57,320
There's no real choice.

70
00:07:58,750 --> 00:08:02,150
I'm going to counter by saying, friends, that in the past 30 years,

71
00:08:02,330 --> 00:08:05,110
There is more scientific data that's come down the pipe

72
00:08:05,110 --> 00:08:07,710
to challenge Darwin's hypothesis

73
00:08:07,710 --> 00:08:10,650
than ever before imagined would come about.

74
00:08:10,930 --> 00:08:14,110
Michael Behe, biochemist from Lehigh University, says this.

75
00:08:14,110 --> 00:08:18,950
The conclusion of intelligent design flows naturally, he says,

76
00:08:19,090 --> 00:08:21,210
from the data itself,

77
00:08:21,810 --> 00:08:24,810
not from sacred books or sectarian beliefs.

78
00:08:25,570 --> 00:08:29,930
The reluctance of science to embrace the conclusion of intelligent design

79
00:08:29,930 --> 00:08:32,770
has no justifiable foundation.

80
00:08:33,630 --> 00:08:37,250
Many people, including many important and well-respected scientists,

81
00:08:38,010 --> 00:08:42,330
just don't want there to be anything beyond nature.

82
00:08:43,730 --> 00:08:44,890
And that's a huge issue.

83
00:08:44,970 --> 00:08:47,430
What he's saying is that the data is pointing somewhere

84
00:08:47,430 --> 00:08:52,390
where many people's worldview doesn't want to allow it to go.

85
00:08:53,470 --> 00:08:57,870
And perhaps many people are holding on to the data that isn't there

86
00:08:57,870 --> 00:09:00,550
or just bits and pieces because of their worldview

87
00:09:00,550 --> 00:09:04,690
doesn't want the conclusion to go where the data is pointing.

88
00:09:07,980 --> 00:09:08,900
Now let me say this.

89
00:09:08,980 --> 00:09:13,540
It is not a disputed point that evolution is true to some extent.

90
00:09:13,860 --> 00:09:16,680
Just by observing the animal and the plant kingdom around you,

91
00:09:16,680 --> 00:09:21,440
it demonstrates that within nature there are variations within a species.

92
00:09:21,820 --> 00:09:24,840
The bottom line is we can breed animals to do different things.

93
00:09:24,940 --> 00:09:27,240
We can make cows give more milk.

94
00:09:27,240 --> 00:09:34,200
We can make subtle changes through the breeding process that allow us to accomplish more with certain animals.

95
00:09:34,600 --> 00:09:37,300
We know that diseases mutate and change.

96
00:09:37,700 --> 00:09:42,480
The mere fact that there's a whole drug industry that comes up with new antibiotics every now and then

97
00:09:42,480 --> 00:09:45,320
is because the little germ buggers mutate.

98
00:09:46,450 --> 00:09:48,530
And I'm susceptible again to that.

99
00:09:48,690 --> 00:09:50,470
I mean, I live out that reality.

100
00:09:51,050 --> 00:09:54,630
I fight them down, they mutate and change, they come back to get me.

101
00:09:55,270 --> 00:09:56,890
We play this battle all day long.

102
00:09:57,150 --> 00:10:01,110
That's because at some micro level, evolution is true.

103
00:10:01,230 --> 00:10:04,970
There are changes within the species.

104
00:10:06,070 --> 00:10:09,410
We can even test this in a test tube or in a petri dish in a laboratory.

105
00:10:09,870 --> 00:10:12,390
You can get little insects, fruit flies and things like that,

106
00:10:12,390 --> 00:10:16,790
and get multiple generations to grow very quickly and notice variations.

107
00:10:17,210 --> 00:10:21,810
We don't dispute that micro, if you will, the small version of evolution is true.

108
00:10:21,810 --> 00:10:27,510
The challenge and the question is, what about what we call macroevolution?

109
00:10:28,150 --> 00:10:31,130
What about the notion, like we just saw up here on the screen,

110
00:10:31,490 --> 00:10:34,010
that through mutations and natural selection,

111
00:10:34,410 --> 00:10:36,830
that is the argument of survival of the fittest,

112
00:10:37,110 --> 00:10:41,010
that animals morph and change into other animals?

113
00:10:41,710 --> 00:10:45,950
Like you saw, the little amoeba moves into a fish that sprouts legs

114
00:10:45,950 --> 00:10:48,170
that begins to crawl up on the beach.

115
00:10:48,170 --> 00:10:52,130
The morphing and changing from one species into another.

116
00:10:53,060 --> 00:10:54,120
What about that?

117
00:10:55,960 --> 00:11:00,200
If you follow the argument, we move from the fish to the land animals,

118
00:11:00,760 --> 00:11:04,500
ultimately to the monkeys, and ultimately to ourselves.

119
00:11:07,580 --> 00:11:09,280
July 23, 2001.

120
00:11:10,490 --> 00:11:12,390
How apes became human.

121
00:11:13,580 --> 00:11:14,160
It's a hot issue.

122
00:11:15,320 --> 00:11:20,620
Every few months or years, a major news magazine will come up with a new issue, a new study.

123
00:11:20,620 --> 00:11:26,020
and when you read it, it's not quite so, the case is not so well closed,

124
00:11:26,360 --> 00:11:31,200
but the way the front article is read, it's an open and shut case.

125
00:11:31,840 --> 00:11:37,340
If you read this in the grocery store line without reading the article, it's a done deal.

126
00:11:41,180 --> 00:11:45,850
The problem is, friends, when you get into the literature, when you really begin to study this,

127
00:11:46,780 --> 00:11:52,040
when you get beyond just the textbooks that come out in the classrooms of the high school students

128
00:11:52,040 --> 00:11:56,260
and the college students, which, by the way, are pulling on data that's usually 20 to 30 years old,

129
00:11:56,620 --> 00:11:59,380
the contemporary thinking is a lot different.

130
00:11:59,500 --> 00:12:06,220
In fact, they're showing now the fossil record doesn't show the process of animals changing into other animals.

131
00:12:08,190 --> 00:12:11,470
In fact, the evidence shows a completely different picture.

132
00:12:12,670 --> 00:12:16,910
Philip Johnson, who is a professor of law at Berkeley,

133
00:12:17,410 --> 00:12:19,070
I want you to catch where he's coming from,

134
00:12:19,070 --> 00:12:26,310
Professor of Law at Berkeley, says when you look back to the rocks dating 570 million years,

135
00:12:26,770 --> 00:12:32,050
there is the sudden appearance of nearly all the animal phyla and they appear to be fully formed.

136
00:12:32,650 --> 00:12:37,170
And he quotes, without a trace of the evolutionary ancestors that Darwinists require.

137
00:12:37,530 --> 00:12:44,650
Now the reason that Johnson gets into this game is because he argues, as a professor of law,

138
00:12:45,090 --> 00:12:47,490
that the data doesn't make the case.

139
00:12:48,940 --> 00:12:52,500
He's arguing from a legal mind

140
00:12:52,500 --> 00:12:55,720
that when you look at all the evolutionary data

141
00:12:55,720 --> 00:12:59,200
and you draw the conclusions that are put out there

142
00:12:59,200 --> 00:13:00,560
about how we evolved,

143
00:13:00,800 --> 00:13:03,300
he says it doesn't add up.

144
00:13:03,840 --> 00:13:05,560
It is not intellectually sound,

145
00:13:05,740 --> 00:13:08,340
and if you were to put this in a court of law,

146
00:13:08,660 --> 00:13:11,940
that the jury would have to find the case null and void,

147
00:13:12,280 --> 00:13:14,740
or perhaps the judge would throw it out.

148
00:13:15,180 --> 00:13:18,460
Professor of Law at Berkeley saying it does not,

149
00:13:19,060 --> 00:13:28,460
add up. His book, by the way, is Darwin on Trial. Well read, good study on that issue.

150
00:13:28,460 --> 00:13:34,140
The fossil record does not point conclusively to the process of evolution. So now the debate

151
00:13:34,140 --> 00:13:41,920
has gone to a microscopic level. I'm going to take you back a little ways to your science

152
00:13:41,920 --> 00:13:49,960
books and perhaps your biology teacher from years ago. Do you remember back in the 1950s

153
00:13:49,960 --> 00:13:57,180
And a gentleman by the name of Stanley Miller did a famous experiment, and he shot electricity,

154
00:13:57,180 --> 00:14:01,900
which was kind of simulating lightning, he shot it through a recreation of the early

155
00:14:01,900 --> 00:14:06,980
building blocks of the Earth's atmosphere, and in some sort of laboratory experiment,

156
00:14:06,980 --> 00:14:12,560
they shot electricity through methane and ammonia and other primordial soup kinds of

157
00:14:12,560 --> 00:14:19,940
materials, and they produced some amino acids, which are some of the building blocks of life.

158
00:14:19,940 --> 00:14:22,400
and it was hailed when it came out

159
00:14:22,400 --> 00:14:25,220
as a death knell for those who believe in God.

160
00:14:25,480 --> 00:14:27,160
It was the end of theism

161
00:14:27,160 --> 00:14:31,320
because they argued with almost a religious fervor

162
00:14:31,320 --> 00:14:34,800
that primitive life could have appeared spontaneously.

163
00:14:36,390 --> 00:14:38,090
And therefore, all of you that go to church,

164
00:14:38,990 --> 00:14:42,990
you're silly because we've created life in the laboratory.

165
00:14:45,730 --> 00:14:47,790
Lee Strobel then interviews in the book

166
00:14:47,790 --> 00:14:48,930
Dr. Walter Bradley,

167
00:14:49,510 --> 00:14:51,710
the retired professor at Texas A&M.

168
00:14:52,910 --> 00:14:54,370
Now, bear with me, it's a little technical,

169
00:14:54,530 --> 00:14:59,230
but he's an expert on chemical polymers and on thermodynamics,

170
00:14:59,230 --> 00:15:04,790
which are two processes that are crucial for the creation of life.

171
00:15:05,450 --> 00:15:08,690
And he is critical of that whole experiment.

172
00:15:09,130 --> 00:15:11,450
He points out that since 1980,

173
00:15:12,390 --> 00:15:15,490
the NASA, the National Air and Space Association administration,

174
00:15:15,890 --> 00:15:19,090
has concluded from their tests in the atmosphere and so forth

175
00:15:19,090 --> 00:15:25,770
that the primitive earth never had any methane, ammonia, or hydrogen to amount to anything.

176
00:15:26,830 --> 00:15:32,110
Instead, the atmosphere was composed of water, carbon dioxide, and nitrogen.

177
00:15:32,530 --> 00:15:36,930
And with those materials, if you shoot electricity through it, you don't get the same results.

178
00:15:38,440 --> 00:15:42,800
And so what he's basically saying is, that's an interesting thing you've done in a laboratory.

179
00:15:43,100 --> 00:15:46,260
By the way, you did it with intelligent design,

180
00:15:46,260 --> 00:15:49,560
because you orchestrated that whole thing to come out

181
00:15:49,560 --> 00:15:51,280
the direction you're hoping it to come out.

182
00:15:51,960 --> 00:15:53,300
But by the way, the initial Earth

183
00:15:53,300 --> 00:15:54,960
had none of those chemicals to begin with,

184
00:15:55,040 --> 00:15:56,720
so it's an interesting little caveat,

185
00:15:57,180 --> 00:15:59,380
but doesn't prove anything.

186
00:16:04,400 --> 00:16:06,260
Is it still possible that chemicals

187
00:16:06,260 --> 00:16:10,280
could in some way self-organize to create a living cell?

188
00:16:11,980 --> 00:16:13,960
We're discovering now in the biological

189
00:16:13,960 --> 00:16:15,460
and molecular biological levels

190
00:16:15,460 --> 00:16:20,300
that the living cell is an extremely complicated little machine.

191
00:16:21,200 --> 00:16:28,820
As a simple cell, for it to do what it does and take in food and replicate and process all of that

192
00:16:28,820 --> 00:16:33,200
requires incredible amounts of information, is incredibly complex.

193
00:16:33,200 --> 00:16:38,260
In fact, it's more complex than anything we can create on one of our supercomputers.

194
00:16:41,060 --> 00:16:44,740
Living cells process energy, store information, replicate.

195
00:16:45,140 --> 00:16:49,140
And for those to spontaneously form, even if you stacked the deck

196
00:16:49,140 --> 00:16:51,700
and placed all the carbon in the universe

197
00:16:51,700 --> 00:16:53,100
on the face of the Earth

198
00:16:53,100 --> 00:16:55,020
and allowed it to chemically react

199
00:16:55,020 --> 00:16:57,640
at the fastest rate possible,

200
00:16:58,080 --> 00:17:00,260
and you left it for a billion years,

201
00:17:01,480 --> 00:17:04,840
the chance that one functional protein molecule would emerge

202
00:17:04,840 --> 00:17:08,840
is 1 in 10 with 60 zeros after it.

203
00:17:11,860 --> 00:17:16,510
Sir Frederick Hoyle described that scenario as likely as this,

204
00:17:16,550 --> 00:17:17,710
and I love this illustration.

205
00:17:18,350 --> 00:17:21,890
Imagine a tornado whirling through a junkyard

206
00:17:21,890 --> 00:17:27,570
and producing a fully functioning Boeing 747 airliner,

207
00:17:29,790 --> 00:17:32,690
that's what it would take.

208
00:17:35,580 --> 00:17:38,160
So not only is the complexity of the living cell

209
00:17:38,160 --> 00:17:40,880
a problem for this random creation process,

210
00:17:41,280 --> 00:17:43,300
but a big problem they're discovering now

211
00:17:43,300 --> 00:17:44,800
is the time required.

212
00:17:45,140 --> 00:17:47,700
And I got this straight from Dr. Hugh Ross at a seminar

213
00:17:47,700 --> 00:17:49,720
and also from Dr. Bradley in the book,

214
00:17:50,060 --> 00:17:51,840
that if you work from the assumption

215
00:17:51,840 --> 00:17:56,230
that the Earth is probably less than 5 billion years old,

216
00:17:56,230 --> 00:18:05,270
Even if the evolutionary process began churning away about five billion years ago, it's not enough time for the process to work.

217
00:18:06,440 --> 00:18:15,310
There's not enough time since, if you argue for a Big Bang, for that to happen, to actually get to those living creatures to begin to do their work.

218
00:18:15,470 --> 00:18:18,290
Complexity is a problem, and so is the time.

219
00:18:20,510 --> 00:18:26,910
Now, in the book, there's a number of other scenarios that are described, and Dr. Bradley summarily kind of discredits.

220
00:18:26,910 --> 00:18:29,570
And I would just encourage you to read that

221
00:18:29,570 --> 00:18:31,170
as you wade through that material.

222
00:18:32,340 --> 00:18:34,000
But I'd like for you now to consider some thoughts

223
00:18:34,000 --> 00:18:35,100
I'm going to put on the screen here.

224
00:18:36,260 --> 00:18:37,680
Klaus Dost, a biochemist,

225
00:18:38,280 --> 00:18:40,760
says more than 30 years of experimentation

226
00:18:40,760 --> 00:18:43,050
on the origin of life

227
00:18:43,050 --> 00:18:45,430
in the fields of chemical and molecular evolution

228
00:18:45,430 --> 00:18:47,510
have led to a better perception

229
00:18:47,510 --> 00:18:50,290
of the immensity of the problem

230
00:18:50,290 --> 00:18:52,640
of the origin of life

231
00:18:52,640 --> 00:18:55,110
rather than to its solution.

232
00:18:56,380 --> 00:19:00,800
At present, all discussions on principle theories and experiments in the field

233
00:19:00,800 --> 00:19:05,520
end either in stalemate or in the confession of ignorance.

234
00:19:08,840 --> 00:19:09,780
Remember Stanley Miller?

235
00:19:10,420 --> 00:19:13,400
The one who did that original experiment back in the 50s?

236
00:19:14,910 --> 00:19:19,050
Well, he said something, a scientific American, in 1991.

237
00:19:20,460 --> 00:19:22,260
He was being interviewed, and he said this.

238
00:19:22,500 --> 00:19:26,400
He said, the problem of the origin of life

239
00:19:26,400 --> 00:19:30,860
has turned out to be much more difficult than I

240
00:19:30,860 --> 00:19:33,420
and most other people envisioned.

241
00:19:35,140 --> 00:19:37,200
Now, is that a classic understatement?

242
00:19:38,260 --> 00:19:39,660
But listen to what he's saying.

243
00:19:40,080 --> 00:19:42,760
The bravado that they had in the early 50s,

244
00:19:42,820 --> 00:19:44,640
that we have solved the mystery,

245
00:19:45,060 --> 00:19:47,700
God is dead, science is king,

246
00:19:47,700 --> 00:19:49,820
and all of this, we have discovered

247
00:19:49,820 --> 00:19:51,560
the early processes of life.

248
00:19:51,960 --> 00:19:54,100
You theists, you God-fearing people,

249
00:19:54,240 --> 00:19:55,260
that's quaint and cute,

250
00:19:55,260 --> 00:20:00,700
But it's irrelevant because science and random process is how we evolved.

251
00:20:01,020 --> 00:20:05,340
And now in 1991, he's saying, you know, it's a little more complicated than that.

252
00:20:08,590 --> 00:20:12,970
Friends, our existence as living, breathing human beings, now more than ever,

253
00:20:13,290 --> 00:20:17,890
in the current scientific literature and elsewhere, is pointing to an intelligent designer.

254
00:20:18,790 --> 00:20:25,940
And we can call that designer God with no fear and no apology.

255
00:20:28,540 --> 00:20:30,720
Chuck Colson, in the book that some of you are studying,

256
00:20:30,900 --> 00:20:33,770
wrote in the book, How Now Shall We Then Live?

257
00:20:34,760 --> 00:20:35,860
He says this poignant thing.

258
00:20:35,940 --> 00:20:40,380
He says, the conclusion is that there are no known physical laws

259
00:20:40,380 --> 00:20:43,600
capable of creating a structure like the DNA

260
00:20:43,600 --> 00:20:46,770
with high information content.

261
00:20:46,770 --> 00:20:49,310
Only an intelligent designer, he writes,

262
00:20:49,390 --> 00:20:51,450
can type out The Night Before Christmas

263
00:20:51,450 --> 00:20:54,130
or devise a computer program

264
00:20:54,130 --> 00:20:56,050
or compose a musical score.

265
00:20:56,050 --> 00:21:02,050
And only an intelligent cause could create the information contained in the DNA molecule.

266
00:21:03,440 --> 00:21:07,640
Isn't it amazing how much information is loaded into our cells?

267
00:21:08,360 --> 00:21:13,720
And whenever else we see something beautiful that we obviously know has intelligent design behind it,

268
00:21:13,880 --> 00:21:19,340
a musical score or a beautiful poem or a novel or any of those things,

269
00:21:19,400 --> 00:21:20,940
we know there's something behind it.

270
00:21:20,940 --> 00:21:23,280
that when we look to the level of the cell and the DNA,

271
00:21:23,660 --> 00:21:27,420
people want to ignore the designer that's behind it.

272
00:21:28,450 --> 00:21:29,930
And it's intellectually foolish.

273
00:21:34,960 --> 00:21:38,420
The whole process of evolution from one species to another is bankrupt.

274
00:21:39,640 --> 00:21:42,200
And I would now even say the concept that's been proposed

275
00:21:42,200 --> 00:21:45,720
as a way to bring these two together called theistic evolution

276
00:21:45,720 --> 00:21:49,680
is not really satisfactory because you don't have to worry about the evolution

277
00:21:49,680 --> 00:21:51,840
because the data doesn't fit it.

278
00:21:51,840 --> 00:21:54,280
We don't have to try and harmonize that together.

279
00:21:55,180 --> 00:21:56,720
The fossil record doesn't work,

280
00:21:58,180 --> 00:22:00,960
and the time doesn't work for the process to evolve.

281
00:22:02,440 --> 00:22:05,880
Friends, there's no concrete evidence that evolution is there.

282
00:22:06,160 --> 00:22:08,720
Alan Sandage, a cosmologist, said this.

283
00:22:09,980 --> 00:22:10,380
He wrote,

284
00:22:11,280 --> 00:22:14,220
How is it that inanimate matter

285
00:22:14,220 --> 00:22:18,630
can organize itself to contemplate itself?

286
00:22:20,140 --> 00:22:20,800
Isn't that amazing?

287
00:22:22,040 --> 00:22:24,440
But that's really what the argument says,

288
00:22:24,440 --> 00:22:26,740
is that the hydrogen and the carbon

289
00:22:26,740 --> 00:22:28,820
and all the great molecules in your body

290
00:22:28,820 --> 00:22:33,240
have organized together to think about how it came together.

291
00:22:34,700 --> 00:22:36,420
That's an amazing issue.

292
00:22:37,850 --> 00:22:40,470
And the cosmologist Ellen Sandage brings that to bear.

293
00:22:41,150 --> 00:22:43,770
Well, I hope I've made the case, at least to this point,

294
00:22:44,010 --> 00:22:45,950
that you're standing on solid ground

295
00:22:45,950 --> 00:22:49,430
when you reject the notion of random Darwinian forces,

296
00:22:49,590 --> 00:22:52,250
when you contemplate how humankind came to existence.

297
00:22:52,550 --> 00:22:55,290
I'm going to argue that God created human beings.

298
00:22:56,330 --> 00:22:58,150
The next question, though, many of us ask is,

299
00:22:58,150 --> 00:22:58,650
Well, how?

300
00:22:59,700 --> 00:23:01,860
And that brings up another whole set of issues.

301
00:23:02,200 --> 00:23:03,860
So now we leave kind of the science,

302
00:23:03,980 --> 00:23:05,900
we leave the cosmologists for a few moments,

303
00:23:06,160 --> 00:23:08,440
and we move to the biblical discussion.

304
00:23:10,750 --> 00:23:12,070
Let's come back to the Bible again.

305
00:23:13,710 --> 00:23:19,760
In the beginning, God created the heavens and the earth.

306
00:23:20,100 --> 00:23:20,960
Genesis 1-1.

307
00:23:24,730 --> 00:23:26,010
I want us to understand

308
00:23:26,010 --> 00:23:29,770
that there's a lot of ongoing research and discussion

309
00:23:29,770 --> 00:23:31,770
and even disagreement

310
00:23:31,770 --> 00:23:34,890
about how God actually created human beings.

311
00:23:35,250 --> 00:23:40,460
The conclusion is coming up as an intelligent designer that has done that.

312
00:23:40,680 --> 00:23:42,620
We can step in and say God created.

313
00:23:43,920 --> 00:23:45,920
But for the purpose now of sharing with a friend

314
00:23:45,920 --> 00:23:51,180
about why you believe that God is a rational position to stand on

315
00:23:51,180 --> 00:23:53,020
and the best answer to our existence,

316
00:23:53,380 --> 00:23:54,920
I hope we've come to that place.

317
00:23:55,380 --> 00:23:56,560
But I want to go further.

318
00:23:57,620 --> 00:24:01,260
Because I have a hunch that many of you would like to know more about the Genesis account.

319
00:24:01,260 --> 00:24:05,400
You're familiar with their Bibles and you know about these six days of creation.

320
00:24:05,400 --> 00:24:12,220
You know a lot about those issues, and you want to know how does that fit with the scientific data that we're talking about.

321
00:24:13,500 --> 00:24:19,960
I'm going to share this morning three dominant views that take Genesis very seriously as the Word of God.

322
00:24:20,680 --> 00:24:24,580
They all take God's special creation of human beings as a literal concept,

323
00:24:25,000 --> 00:24:29,240
and yet they all reject the Darwinian forces as an answer to our existence.

324
00:24:29,660 --> 00:24:32,000
And these three viewpoints are very different, though.

325
00:24:32,700 --> 00:24:34,320
The book, The Genesis Debate,

326
00:24:35,000 --> 00:24:37,040
that just came out a few months ago,

327
00:24:38,590 --> 00:24:41,790
I dashed through this in preparation for this,

328
00:24:41,870 --> 00:24:44,110
and I found this to be a profound book,

329
00:24:44,450 --> 00:24:46,470
well-researched and well-presented

330
00:24:46,470 --> 00:24:50,430
of the three different debates about the creation story,

331
00:24:51,130 --> 00:24:53,950
and then rebuttals back and forth from all the characters,

332
00:24:53,950 --> 00:24:56,190
and by the time you're done, your head can spin,

333
00:24:56,550 --> 00:24:59,730
and you realize there's a lot of discussion in this area.

334
00:24:59,730 --> 00:25:08,280
As the first chapter of Genesis unfolds, we are presented with six creation days and God

335
00:25:08,280 --> 00:25:09,280
resting on the seventh.

336
00:25:09,540 --> 00:25:11,400
How are we to understand these days?

337
00:25:11,860 --> 00:25:13,820
Are they 24-hour periods of time?

338
00:25:14,140 --> 00:25:17,740
Are they long periods of time, perhaps millions of years?

339
00:25:17,980 --> 00:25:21,940
Or are they literary devices that sidestep science and time altogether?

340
00:25:23,240 --> 00:25:24,360
So here are the three views.

341
00:25:25,680 --> 00:25:29,020
They're called the 24-hour view, point A,

342
00:25:29,440 --> 00:25:34,750
or the day-age view, or the framework view.

343
00:25:37,470 --> 00:25:39,530
Now before we get into this, I want to be very clear

344
00:25:39,530 --> 00:25:45,920
that the issue surrounding the creation is not a salvation issue.

345
00:25:47,100 --> 00:25:50,220
This is not an issue that should split our churches.

346
00:25:50,580 --> 00:25:53,880
This is not an issue that should cause us to be suspicious of each other.

347
00:25:53,880 --> 00:25:57,260
Oh, he holds 24-hour view. Oh, we can't fellowship together.

348
00:25:57,520 --> 00:25:59,300
That kind of stuff is ridiculous.

349
00:25:59,760 --> 00:26:04,910
because earnest, intelligent, God-loving, Bible-believing,

350
00:26:05,290 --> 00:26:06,510
saved-by-the-blood-of-Jesus,

351
00:26:06,670 --> 00:26:08,310
filled-with-the-Holy-Spirit kind of people

352
00:26:08,310 --> 00:26:11,550
are found representing all three of these views.

353
00:26:12,890 --> 00:26:16,310
So we need to sort of step back as believers in Scripture

354
00:26:16,310 --> 00:26:20,900
and not fight about this so vehemently.

355
00:26:22,380 --> 00:26:25,960
I think it forces us to sort of investigate for ourselves

356
00:26:25,960 --> 00:26:28,200
where we might come out on these issues.

357
00:26:29,290 --> 00:26:32,110
But there's good reason to look at all three of them

358
00:26:32,110 --> 00:26:32,970
and take them seriously.

359
00:26:33,450 --> 00:26:36,050
The first one is the 24-hour view.

360
00:26:37,330 --> 00:26:40,390
And this position takes a straightforward reading

361
00:26:40,390 --> 00:26:41,970
of the first chapter of Genesis

362
00:26:41,970 --> 00:26:44,690
and argues that if God is a God of miracles,

363
00:26:45,110 --> 00:26:46,750
then he can do whatever he wants,

364
00:26:46,810 --> 00:26:49,870
and if he so chooses to create in 24-hour cycles,

365
00:26:50,210 --> 00:26:52,170
that's his business, his prerogative,

366
00:26:52,390 --> 00:26:54,610
and there's no way for us to say he could

367
00:26:54,610 --> 00:26:56,130
or could not have done it that way.

368
00:26:57,060 --> 00:26:58,080
It's a logical position.

369
00:27:00,320 --> 00:27:01,860
So here's the strengths of this argument.

370
00:27:02,300 --> 00:27:03,380
Number one, it's straightforward.

371
00:27:04,990 --> 00:27:06,370
It's theologically sound.

372
00:27:08,020 --> 00:27:11,060
Much of the early church believed that position.

373
00:27:12,410 --> 00:27:16,690
And it rejects kind of an accommodation to the spirit of the age,

374
00:27:16,790 --> 00:27:19,350
kind of to this intellectual or chronological snobbery

375
00:27:19,350 --> 00:27:22,870
that is assuming that every new idea is better than an old idea,

376
00:27:23,170 --> 00:27:25,690
that every new idea is superior.

377
00:27:25,690 --> 00:27:28,810
It just says, God says this.

378
00:27:29,390 --> 00:27:30,630
He's a miracle worker.

379
00:27:32,100 --> 00:27:33,660
It can make sense, straightforward.

380
00:27:33,660 --> 00:27:38,040
And the early church fathers, by and large, took this position.

381
00:27:39,070 --> 00:27:40,250
That's the 24-hour view.

382
00:27:41,380 --> 00:27:42,360
It has good merit.

383
00:27:44,110 --> 00:27:52,160
The day-age view sees the days of creation as ages of long duration.

384
00:27:53,930 --> 00:27:59,270
This view highly values both the revelation that comes from Scripture

385
00:27:59,270 --> 00:28:03,770
and also the revelation that comes as we observe nature

386
00:28:03,770 --> 00:28:06,190
and test it and put it through its paces.

387
00:28:06,190 --> 00:28:16,830
It wants to integrate those two as that God made the earth and God reveals himself in scripture and we can discern things from about him as we look at both.

388
00:28:17,930 --> 00:28:28,790
This view does a great job of harmonizing the creation account that the scientific model about a hot big bang about five billion years ago would have brought about.

389
00:28:29,350 --> 00:28:34,130
And so the strengths here are it is consistent with current science.

390
00:28:35,390 --> 00:28:36,670
It's testable.

391
00:28:37,790 --> 00:28:41,690
The proponents of this view are talking about how the creation days

392
00:28:41,690 --> 00:28:45,670
do line up with how, over various millions of years,

393
00:28:46,130 --> 00:28:49,510
the earth would be changing and getting ready for life.

394
00:28:49,610 --> 00:28:50,950
And they take that very seriously.

395
00:28:53,280 --> 00:28:56,240
And they can test, if they work from certain assumptions,

396
00:28:56,360 --> 00:29:00,560
they can test for and find out if those values are true.

397
00:29:00,640 --> 00:29:05,540
And they can look for things in current chemistry and biology and physics

398
00:29:05,540 --> 00:29:06,880
that would back up their view.

399
00:29:06,920 --> 00:29:08,040
And they can find those things.

400
00:29:08,040 --> 00:29:11,420
And they continue to find those things almost on a daily basis.

401
00:29:12,080 --> 00:29:15,740
It's testable, and it's also theologically sound.

402
00:29:18,060 --> 00:29:20,500
The last one is the framework view.

403
00:29:21,960 --> 00:29:27,090
And the framework view really sees those creation days

404
00:29:27,090 --> 00:29:31,750
as a literary device that the author of the book of Genesis

405
00:29:31,750 --> 00:29:37,310
used to teach incredibly powerful theological principles.

406
00:29:38,290 --> 00:29:40,430
And I'm going to kind of read through them.

407
00:29:41,160 --> 00:29:43,560
First of all, looking at creation kingdoms.

408
00:29:43,740 --> 00:29:45,200
Day one is light.

409
00:29:46,530 --> 00:29:49,910
Day two then comes the sky and the seas.

410
00:29:51,580 --> 00:29:54,480
Day three is the dry land and the vegetation.

411
00:29:56,350 --> 00:29:59,530
And then starting on day four are the creatures,

412
00:30:00,330 --> 00:30:03,710
the kings, if you will, that take over and dominate those kingdoms.

413
00:30:03,710 --> 00:30:05,710
So going back to day one and day four,

414
00:30:06,130 --> 00:30:10,250
the luminaries are in the realm where there is light.

415
00:30:11,840 --> 00:30:15,440
And number day five, the sea creatures and the winged creatures

416
00:30:15,440 --> 00:30:22,610
fulfill and fill the area where the skies and the sea are the kingdoms to fill.

417
00:30:24,460 --> 00:30:27,800
And day six, the land animals and eventually human beings,

418
00:30:28,200 --> 00:30:32,870
they fill up what day three created, the dry land and the vegetation.

419
00:30:34,910 --> 00:30:37,130
And then you go to the creator king of day seven,

420
00:30:38,100 --> 00:30:39,200
who's lord of the Sabbath.

421
00:30:39,660 --> 00:30:44,080
And that model comes directly out of this book on page 224.

422
00:30:45,690 --> 00:30:49,830
The framework view is also theologically sound.

423
00:30:51,260 --> 00:30:53,360
It's not contrary to science.

424
00:30:53,660 --> 00:30:55,720
It's not even really bound to science.

425
00:30:55,960 --> 00:30:58,400
It just sort of sidesteps the issue and says,

426
00:30:58,400 --> 00:31:01,180
whatever science finds, that's okay,

427
00:31:01,500 --> 00:31:04,760
because the author is communicating theological truth to us.

428
00:31:08,240 --> 00:31:13,520
And number three, it's got strong literary and theological content in that view.

429
00:31:16,750 --> 00:31:19,230
In sum, this is where I'm going to come out now,

430
00:31:20,560 --> 00:31:25,780
I view each of these views as having something to contribute valuable to the debate.

431
00:31:26,630 --> 00:31:29,090
I also find when studying a book like this

432
00:31:29,090 --> 00:31:33,430
that each view kind of camps on one issue

433
00:31:33,430 --> 00:31:36,580
and really goes to town on that issue

434
00:31:36,580 --> 00:31:38,820
and in some ways talks past the other ones.

435
00:31:40,240 --> 00:31:41,860
Even when they rebut each other,

436
00:31:41,860 --> 00:31:46,240
they're not really addressing directly all the issues raised each time.

437
00:31:46,520 --> 00:31:48,600
They grab one part of the position that they like,

438
00:31:48,600 --> 00:31:52,860
They run with it strongly, but they still somewhat miss.

439
00:31:53,180 --> 00:31:57,280
And it shows the complexity and the breadth of the issue,

440
00:31:57,420 --> 00:31:59,120
because there's many different ways to look at it.

441
00:31:59,460 --> 00:32:01,220
At this point in my own journey,

442
00:32:02,370 --> 00:32:06,910
I'm finding myself coming somewhere in a synthesis, a hybrid,

443
00:32:07,350 --> 00:32:10,550
of both the day-age view and the literary view,

444
00:32:12,220 --> 00:32:13,380
but I'm still working it out.

445
00:32:15,250 --> 00:32:18,330
I find you can actually hold those two views almost simultaneously

446
00:32:18,330 --> 00:32:21,050
without much shifting or maneuvering,

447
00:32:21,170 --> 00:32:22,950
and you can actually see them

448
00:32:22,950 --> 00:32:24,850
almost as layers on top of each other.

449
00:32:27,940 --> 00:32:31,560
But I urge you all to study and pray

450
00:32:31,560 --> 00:32:33,940
and see where the quest will take you

451
00:32:33,940 --> 00:32:37,130
because it's a fascinating journey

452
00:32:37,130 --> 00:32:39,110
and worthy of getting on that road

453
00:32:39,110 --> 00:32:41,390
and seeing what God will say.

454
00:32:42,770 --> 00:32:44,510
To recap, I just want to say this.

455
00:32:46,010 --> 00:32:48,570
Friends, you are standing on solid ground

456
00:32:48,570 --> 00:32:51,220
when you affirm to the world

457
00:32:51,220 --> 00:32:54,620
that God created you and me.

458
00:32:55,690 --> 00:32:57,450
You are neither a monkey's uncle

459
00:32:57,450 --> 00:32:59,450
nor a monkey's child.

460
00:33:00,920 --> 00:33:02,520
And whatever you may read at the zoo

461
00:33:02,520 --> 00:33:05,700
or listen to headphones as you tour the animal parks

462
00:33:05,700 --> 00:33:06,640
and all these things,

463
00:33:06,960 --> 00:33:09,020
you did not evolve from the animals.

464
00:33:09,140 --> 00:33:10,760
There's no data to support that.

465
00:33:10,760 --> 00:33:14,140
Friends, that position is more religion than science.

466
00:33:15,680 --> 00:33:17,140
You are a special human being

467
00:33:17,140 --> 00:33:19,300
created to manage God's creation

468
00:33:19,300 --> 00:33:21,420
and to have relationship with God

469
00:33:21,420 --> 00:33:22,900
and with each other.

470
00:33:23,920 --> 00:33:26,220
And I hope I've made the case this morning

471
00:33:26,220 --> 00:33:30,280
that a belief in God is a rational proposition,

472
00:33:30,780 --> 00:33:34,080
that it requires a God with all the creative powers

473
00:33:34,080 --> 00:33:36,920
beyond our ability to create such complex

474
00:33:36,920 --> 00:33:39,740
and special creatures as you and I.

475
00:33:40,320 --> 00:33:43,160
And if I've not made the case and slammed it shut,

476
00:33:43,400 --> 00:33:45,760
it's my hope that I've brought you at least to a place

477
00:33:45,760 --> 00:33:48,040
of questioning what you've been receiving

478
00:33:48,040 --> 00:33:49,500
from different sources,

479
00:33:49,500 --> 00:33:52,240
and that it will drive you on your own journey

480
00:33:52,240 --> 00:33:55,300
to investigate and search out truth

481
00:33:55,300 --> 00:33:58,180
and to find God in the process.

482
00:33:58,900 --> 00:34:01,020
And so my challenge to you and my blessing would be

483
00:34:01,020 --> 00:34:04,200
may God bless you in that process.

484
00:34:05,890 --> 00:34:06,870
And now would you pray with me?

485
00:34:07,980 --> 00:34:12,060
Our Father and our God and our Creator,

486
00:34:13,680 --> 00:34:15,680
thank you again for the privilege of life.

487
00:34:17,050 --> 00:34:20,390
Thank you that as we investigate more closely

488
00:34:20,390 --> 00:34:23,360
the reality that you created,

489
00:34:23,360 --> 00:34:27,440
that we begin to see your fingerprint on the very creation.

490
00:34:28,990 --> 00:34:31,070
And I pray, Father, that the words we've talked about

491
00:34:31,070 --> 00:34:32,830
and all the different scientists we've quoted

492
00:34:32,830 --> 00:34:37,410
and all of this data would begin to push us

493
00:34:37,410 --> 00:34:40,670
further along in the journey, our intellectual quest,

494
00:34:41,210 --> 00:34:44,010
what would put us on solid ground as we share with others.

495
00:34:46,320 --> 00:34:48,580
And, Father, you'd use this for our own edification

496
00:34:48,580 --> 00:34:52,250
and for evangelism as we share the truth with others.

497
00:34:53,320 --> 00:34:55,140
Father, this world needs to be liberated

498
00:34:55,140 --> 00:34:57,540
from the idea that life is meaningless

499
00:34:57,540 --> 00:35:03,590
because we're just advanced forms of sea slime.

500
00:35:06,440 --> 00:35:08,260
Father, you have a purpose for our lives.

501
00:35:09,220 --> 00:35:13,700
And you created us for that purpose.

502
00:35:14,840 --> 00:35:16,220
May each of us find that,

503
00:35:17,380 --> 00:35:18,500
be rooted in that,

504
00:35:19,540 --> 00:35:20,700
be strengthened in that,

505
00:35:22,180 --> 00:35:24,300
and operate in ministry out of that place.

506
00:35:26,180 --> 00:35:28,040
Father, pour out your spirit upon us today.

507
00:35:28,200 --> 00:35:30,100
Encourage us with the truth of your word.

508
00:35:32,090 --> 00:35:34,330
Help us understand how it all fits together.

509
00:35:34,330 --> 00:35:42,810
and bless us, we ask, as we continue to marvel at who you are

510
00:35:42,810 --> 00:35:44,790
and the goodness of creation.

511
00:35:46,500 --> 00:35:47,440
We thank you for it.

512
00:35:48,880 --> 00:35:51,500
So, Father, as we sing these final words of these songs,

513
00:35:53,150 --> 00:35:54,150
do your work this morning.

514
00:35:55,180 --> 00:35:57,860
Touch our lives and draw us closer to you.

515
00:35:59,350 --> 00:36:00,490
We pray this in Jesus' name.

516
00:36:02,500 --> 00:36:03,900
I'm going to invite you to stand.

517
00:36:05,010 --> 00:36:06,750
And if there's a need in your life, as always,

518
00:36:06,750 --> 00:36:09,230
we welcome you to come as we sing these final songs.

519
00:36:10,100 --> 00:36:11,880
If you'd like some prayer, you just come down here

520
00:36:11,880 --> 00:36:13,100
and one of our leaders will come

521
00:36:13,100 --> 00:36:14,560
and just pray with you

522
00:36:14,560 --> 00:36:15,640
or answer some questions.

523
00:36:16,300 --> 00:36:17,760
But feel like this is a time for ministry

524
00:36:17,760 --> 00:36:19,340
and for receiving from the Lord something.

525
00:36:19,520 --> 00:36:20,360
So you feel free to come

526
00:36:20,360 --> 00:36:22,240
if that's your need this morning.

527
00:36:23,230 --> 00:36:23,990
Today would you lead us.

528
00:36:42,080 --> 00:38:55,470
Be a day of fun.

529
00:38:56,610 --> 00:39:01,840
Be blessed as you leave in Jesus' name.

